SUMMARY:*Sold Out* OlioTrip Morocco: Music\, Spirit & Living Tradition
DESCRIPTION:OlioTrip Morocco: Music\, Spirit &amp\; Living Tradition&nbsp\;
 May 22–29\, 2026*This trip is sold out*OverviewThis OlioTrip\, curated i
 n collaboration with LILA and led by Moroccan Gnawa musician Samir Langus\
 , offers an immersive experience of Morocco through the interconnected len
 ses of music\, culture\, and spirituality. As always\, our trips are desig
 ned as a relational\, place-based immersion - the kind of trip that only h
 appens when you are moving around with locals. Traversing from the Atlanti
 c coast to historic port cities and into the rural countryside\, Samir and
  the people of LILA and Olio will curate the experience every step of the 
 way so that you can let go and fully enjoy every step of cobblestone and e
 ach wave of the Atlantic.&nbsp\;Our group will engage with Morocco through
  sound\, story\, and lived tradition: exploring Gnawa music and its spirit
 ual roots\, learning about Morocco’s interwoven Muslim and Jewish histor
 ies\, and connecting with local ecological practices. Throughout the week 
 our activities will emphasizes depth\, presence\, and cultural exchange\, 
 creating space for both learning and integration.Rough ItineraryMay 22–2
 4: AgadirThe journey begins in Agadir\, a coastal gateway where contempora
 ry Morocco meets long-standing tradition. We ease into the experience thro
 ugh the relaxed surf culture and beach village life of Taghazoute\, offeri
 ng time to acclimate and connect with the sea.Our group will then travel t
 o the hometown of our guide\, Samir Langus\, for an intimate\, family-styl
 e welcome! This gathering centers Moroccan hospitality\, shared meals\, an
 d a live musical experience\, offering a rare introduction to local life t
 hrough personal relationships. This opening chapter sets the tone for the 
 week\, but it will be hard to leave this relaxing beach town.May 24–27: 
 EssaouiraEssaouira has long been a crossroads of cultures\, shaped by Afri
 can\, Arab\, Amazigh\, and Jewish influences. Known for its windswept ramp
 arts\, artistic spirit\, and historic medina\, the city holds a unique pla
 ce in Morocco’s cultural and spiritual landscape.Here\, participants wil
 l engage deeply with Gnawa music\, learning directly from local musicians 
 about its ancestral roots\, ceremonial role\, and spiritual dimensions. Pr
 ogramming will also explore the Jewish history of Morocco\, with a focus o
 n Essaouira’s once-thriving Jewish community and its enduring legacy.Tim
 e will be balanced between guided learning and open exploration—wanderin
 g the medina\, connecting with artisans\, and absorbing the creative\, con
 templative energy that defines the city. We'll eat well at every meal and 
 enjoy the nightlife of dancing and music in this lovely city.May 27–29: 
 Retreat at an Eco-Permaculture Center in BoulouaneThe final phase of the O
 liotrip brings the group inland to a riverside eco-permaculture retreat ce
 nter in Boulouane\, offering space for integration and grounding. Surround
 ed by nature\, these days are designed to slow the pace and synthesize the
  experiences of the previous week.&nbsp\;We will learn about local agricul
 tural practices and food systems\, engage in a hands-on cooking workshop u
 sing ingredients grown on site\, and share communal meals rooted in region
 al tradition. The journey concludes with a closing concert featuring a mus
 ic group local to the area—bringing together land\, sound\, and collecti
 ve experience as a meaningful closing ritual.*Our group trip ends here but
  if you can swing it\, we encourage you to travel to one of the old cities
  in Morocco (or return to your favorite place from the Oliotrip) - we will
  be happy to offer some recommendations!&nbsp\;--Your Guide:Samir LanGus i
 s a Grammy-nominated musician\, born and raised in the city of Agadir\, Mo
 rocco. Music has always been a part of the constant variety of street soun
 ds of his city\, from merchants to entertainers and calls to prayer. LanGu
 s began learning Gnawa\, a traditional\, spiritual trance music\, at an ea
 rly age from the Gnawa masters of Morocco\, especially Maalem Hamid El Kas
 ri.&nbsp\;For the uninitiated\, Gnawa music is the ritual trance music of 
 Morocco’s Black communities\, originally descended from the enslaved peo
 ple and soldiers once brought to Morocco from northern Mali and Mauritania
 . Often called “The Moroccan Blues\,” Gnawa music has a raw\, hypnotic
  power that fascinated outsiders as diverse as writer/composer Paul Bowles
 \, jazz giant Randy Weston\, and rock god Jimi Hendrix.&nbsp\;--Reflection
 s on our trip to Guatemala last year:"Shoutout to Think Olio and Guatemala
  and a very special group of people who provided me the space to experienc
 e and be witness to love\, care\, connection\, joy\, vulnerability\, humil
 ity\, healing\, wonder\, and so much goddamn fun." - Nicole R.--Full price
  for the 8 day trip:&nbsp\;Shared room $3000. Private Room $3500.$500 depo
 sit to reserve your spot!&nbsp\;Balance to be paid in full by April 15.Rea
 ch out for payment plan options.&nbsp\;Included:Accommodations (7 nights)A
 ll breakfasts\, 3 lunches and 3 dinnersAll workshops\, tours\, and activit
 iesTransportation to/from activitiesTips for drivers &amp\; guides | &nbsp
 \;Not Included:Flights to/from Morocco&nbsp\;Meals not listedTravel insura
 ncePersonal expenses\n\nTickets & info: https://www.viewcy.com/event/oliot
 rip_morocco_art
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/oliotrip_morocco_art
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:02fd8b86-57a5-447b-95c4-d952ff42b0ae@viewcy.olio
DTSTAMP:20260524T140306Z
DTSTART:20260602T233000Z
DTEND:20260603T013000Z
SUMMARY:The Jaws of Hell: Writing the Afterlife
DESCRIPTION:The Jaws of Hell: Writing the Afterlife Tuesday evenings at 7:3
 0pm\, June 2nd\, 9th\, 16th\, &amp\; 23rd at the Olio LighthouseHell isn
 ’t always depicted as fire and brimstone\; sometimes it's an infinite li
 brary\, an AI generated wasteland\, or a hotel room with passive aggressiv
 e strangers. In this hybrid class we'll first critically examine hellish f
 iction\, analyzing what makes these strange afterlifes so gruesome—and a
 lluring. Genres will range: poetry\, novella\, short story\, stage play\, 
 and visual art.&nbsp\;Join writer and professor Alexandra Dos Santos in th
 is 4-week Olio workshop where you'll take inspiration from class readings 
 to create your own underworlds. Each session will include writing prompts 
 and exercises based on the week's story. Through mini group workshops and 
 partner critiques\, you’ll get instant feedback on your fresh ideas\, he
 lping your story take shape early on.&nbsp\;By the second class\, please r
 ead the novella A Short Stay in Hell by Steven L. Peck (108 pages). This i
 s the only text you will have to get on your own. It's widely available in
  libraries or online bookstores. You can also buy the E-book in a pinch!&n
 bsp\;Class One: Introduction: personal interpretations of hell and demons:
  tropes\, stereotypes. Dig into what molds preconceptions\, and briefly ex
 amine historical and artistic context. Appetizer of hellish excerpts for a
  general foundation on hell in literature. In class writing: exercises bas
 ed on visual depictions of hell.For next class: continue or finish reading
  A Short Stay in Hell by Steven L. Peck Class Two: Discuss: A Short Stay i
 n Hell. Thematic analysis: cosmic horror\, identity\, existential dread. C
 raft analysis: SETTINGIn class writing exercise: devise your own unlikely 
 setting for hell. For next class\, read short story: “I Have No Mouth an
 d I Must Scream” by Harlan Ellison&nbsp\;Class Three: Discuss: “I Have
  No Mouth and I Must Scream.” Thematic analysis: what's a secular hell? 
 Modernity\, AI\, individualism. Craft analysis: SYMBOLIn class writing exe
 rcise: create your own devil\, demons or underworld spirits.&nbsp\; For ne
 xt class\, read or watch the play No Exit by Jean-Paul SartreClass Four:Di
 scuss: No Exit. Thematic analysis: the hell of the mind\, relationships\, 
 and the "hungry ghost". Craft analysis: DIALOGUE AND CHARACTER. &nbsp\;In 
 class writing exercise: dialogue to generate conflict&nbsp\;What to expect
 :&nbsp\;Genre exploration through curated readings and art about hell\, de
 mons\, and the soul&nbsp\;Special focus on different craft elements each w
 eek based on the reading: symbolism\, setting\, dialogue and characterGrou
 p discussions on what hell means to us based on our unique experiences\, a
 nd how to alchemize it into art&nbsp\;Generative exercises to help mold fe
 ar\, shame\, suffering\, desire\, and even curiosity into hellish concepts
  and stories&nbsp\;Peer feedback on fresh work created in class through sm
 all groups and pairsAbout Your Instructor:Alexandra Dos Santos is a writer
  and College Writing instructor based in Astoria\, New York\, with an MFA 
 from The Writers Foundry at St. Joseph's University. Her work spans horror
 \, the esoteric\, and the speculative\, appearing in Electric Literature\,
  Lithub\, Flash Fiction Magazine\, and Vol. 1 Brooklyn\, among others. She
 's led creative writing workshops throughout Brooklyn and received fellows
 hips from Wildacres Writers Retreat and the Disquiet International Literar
 y Program.*Writers of all levels are welcome here!\n\nTickets & info: http
 s://www.viewcy.com/event/the_jaws_of_hell_wri
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/the_jaws_of_hell_wri
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:eefe0ec8-4bb4-434d-80b3-59c99267b616@viewcy.olio
DTSTAMP:20260524T140306Z
DTSTART:20260611T230000Z
DTEND:20260612T010000Z
SUMMARY:The Ecstasy of Beauty w/ Dr. Adluri
DESCRIPTION:In light of the 'Raphael: Sublime Poetry' exhibit at the Metrop
 olitan Museum of Art this Olio will explore questions such as what is the 
 connection between beauty and philosophy?&nbsp\;This Olio offers a guided 
 appreciation of the main works in the Met’s Raphael exhibition\, providi
 ng historical context and a philosophical thread that connects each key pi
 ece—so that moving through the galleries becomes\, in effect\, a lesson 
 in how Raphael makes the intellect emanate through vision.Professor Adluri
  introduces Raphael as the Renaissance master who makes an audacious claim
  with paint: beauty is not mere sensation\, but a mode of truth.&nbsp\;Thi
 s Olio frames Raphael’s art through a philosophy where visible harmony b
 ecomes a pathway to the invisible\, where proportion\, clarity\, and grace
  train the mind toward higher reality. A hallmark of Raphael’s genius is
  that his use of proportion\, forms\, and colors does more than represent 
 bodies: it suggests an inner order\, as if form itself were an argument. I
 n this vision\, beauty is not simply what pleases the eye\; it educates de
 sire\, drawing the viewer from surface appearance toward the intelligible 
 principles that our intellect naturally seeks.After the Olio we'll facilit
 ate a group trip to the MET at a later date with people from this class so
  that we can enjoy the exhibit with our newfound perspective.--Raphael: Su
 blime Poetry exhibit is on display at the Metropolitan Museum of Art\, NY 
 through June 28th\, 2026.&nbsp\; In Time Out’s words\, the exhibit is a 
 “once-in-a-generation” event—offering a rare chance to see Raphael a
 t full scale: incredible paintings\, drawings\, and ambitious designs that
  showcase his range\, speed\, and polish as much as for his famous sweetne
 ss and grace. The New York Times calls it a true blockbuster—rapturous\,
  even—while The Wall Street Journal raves about its staggering versatili
 ty across media and the clarity of its biographical sweep. The Washington 
 Post likewise calls it a major event\, Hyperallergic admires the feat of s
 ecuring the loans and the exhibition’s sense of historic arrival\, and A
 rtnet News admires the show’s seriousness while suggesting Raphael’s r
 adiance reads best when the era’s power and politics are allowed to cast
  a faint shadow across the beauty. Frieze echoes these superlatives\, call
 ing it a “once-in-a-lifetime chance.”Evening Flow7:00 PM – Doors ope
 n. Settle in\, grab a drink\, and meet a friend.7:30 PM – The Olio begin
 s: an intimate\, interactive lecture and guided exploration.8:30 PM – In
 stead of a traditional Q&amp\;A\, we shift into a social experience—disc
 ussing ideas with others in the room while the teacher joins and floats be
 tween conversations.10:00 PM - Last call at the bar and we'll start to win
 d down the evening.What Is an Olio?Think Olio is an ongoing experiment in 
 lifelong learning. We are a community of open-minded people who gather to 
 exchange ideas with new friends and connect over art\, literature\, and ph
 ilosophy.Check out our full calendarOur $30 membership gives you two event
 s for the price of one!&nbsp\;An Olio is what we call the social learning 
 events we’ve been organizing since 2015. A blend between a lecture and a
  house party\, Olios are led by a teacher who loves sharing their passions
  and the room is filled with curious\, open-minded New Yorkers.&nbsp\;Our 
 goal is to spark new perspectives\, ignite curiosity\, and enjoy ourselves
  socially—an alternative to typical nightlife options.Disclaimer: By pur
 chasing a ticket\, you agree to have your photo/video used for social medi
 a/marketing materials. If you prefer to not have your photo taken\, feel f
 ree to send us a note. Photo by Zhi-Da Zhong\n\nTickets & info: https://ww
 w.viewcy.com/event/the_ecstasy_of_beauty
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/the_ecstasy_of_beauty
END:VEVENT
